The south-west border region of Bangladesh with India, close to the Sundarbans mangrove forest has some of the most vulnerable districts to climate change. At the same time the region is a hot spot for trafficking and modern slavery. On the Indian side of the border there are high levels of trafficking and in Bangladesh forced labour, child exploitation and trafficking are rife. The whole area is hugely vulnerable to climate change, including high intensity cyclones and sea level rise. Floods and tidal surges frequently breach embankments, flooding areas with saline water which destroys crops and drinking water. The loss of land, livelihoods and decreasing productivity trigger migration. With more and more people looking to migrate, they rely increasingly on trafficking networks. Those most vulnerable are women from women headed households, children, and men from extreme poor families. Victims are forced into hard labour working in sweatshops or in construction with others being forced into prostitution. Modern slavery conditions can also be found in the Sundarbans region, including labour exploitation through fish and shrimp production and processing, as well as brick kilns where debt bondage is common. 

With this in mind, CAFOD has developed an 18-month pilot initiative which aims to support research and then scale interventions which address issues of climate change and modern slavery in the Sundarbans (both in Bangladesh and India). The project will start by forming a partnership with a leading academic institution  or organisation to conduct a detailed assessment of the link in the Sundarbans (both in Bangladesh and India) between climate change, environmental degradation, migration and modern slavery. The findings of this study will be used to inform and refine project activities with aim to reduce the prevalence of people most affected by climate change and environmental degradation falling into modern slavery.

The main purpose of the HCS Transition project is to enable local and national organisations such as CCFN to improve the quality and effectiveness of their humanitarian preparedness and response capacity. This will be done through a process of capacity self-assessment and capacity strengthening action planning, Training of Trainers and cascading of learning on key emergency response and volunteer topics, and peer learning between the 9 organisations involved in the programme. CAFOD staff will provide support throughout this process.

The proposed objectives are:
•	Uphold agreed partner commitments for a further 1 year of support in Nigeria, Zimbabwe and Liberia.  
•	Support PEOPLE partners to continue to embed learning, policies and processes developed during PEOPLE.
•	Capture learning on the longer-term impact of capacity strengthening support to PEOPLE.
•	Involve existing partners and the CS team in piloting new approaches and developing CS tools.
•	Facilitate peer exchange between HCS and CAFOD staff and partners from other countries to share expertise and promote different CS approaches.
•	Learning from the transition phase and HCS experiences to date will feed into the development of a CS strategy and approach for the international programme.

The overall objective of this project is to provide an improved inclusive WASH, food security and livelihood services, and Protection through enhancing the contribution of civil society, particularly women and youths in 2 localities of Khartoum State (Um Bada,). 

Project Outcome and Output:
FSL Theme

 Targeted communities trained on CP mechanisms.

This project aims to contribute to the protection of girls, children from abuse, Child labour in mining areas and help them to re-integrate into normal and/or recuperation schooling system while strengthening the livelihood means around their family livelihood systems. It is a 30-month project. 

The project will seek to significantly reduce child labour in mining areas by providing sustainable alternative livelihood opportunities to parents. The project will be undertaken in  Kabare and Walungu territories in South Kivu Province, DRC. The project will seek to reach a total of 1750 direct participants and 5500 indirect participants.
This will include entrepreneurship training on small start-up businesses of their choice and the provision of start-up funds which will develop to establishing links with other local existing credit access firms intended to the parents for sustainability purpose. Increase access to and support for primary education, particularly in mining communities. In order to maximize the impact of this activity, the activity will be done through the parent (preferably mothers) of the child who will benefit from the income generating activity in order to be able to pay the school fees of the child in the local school. In the same line, it will also strengthen the family livelihood means helping the child to have food in order to divert the attention of the parent to send them to work in the mining. This support will be extended to children especially girls who are unable to continue to secondary schools due to their inability to pay school fees.

By combining short-term and long-term support for survivors of abuse and exploitation across 8 districts in Bangladesh, with advocacy activities to improve Government-provided services, this project will aim to reduce risky remigration by vulnerable migrants workers and survivors of exploitation and abuse through recovery, reintegration, and economic support when they return to Bangladesh. The project will build on the experience of the consortium members with CAFOD as the lead agency providing capacity strengthening to its partners, Caritas Bangladesh leading activities providing sustainable employment options and start up businesses for survivors, and OKUP providing access to shelter, psychosocial counselling, medical referrals, legal aid, family reunification and dispute resolution. The project will also work with the Bangladesh Government to advocate for improved reintegration services, especially for the most vulnerable women returnee migrant workers. 

The project is funded by the Global Fund to End Modern Slavery (GFEMS), with funding via GFEMS coming from NORAD (Norwegian Government)

CTP and its partners TOCH and ADA with technical support form SELCO are embarking on a energy need assessment in South Sudan and the focus will be in Juba (IDPs Camps) and Gogrial (Kuajok). These locations are chosen based on strong location presence of implementing partners (ADA working in Juba and TOCH working in Gogrial). The assessment will focus on pastoralist, farmers (Crop framers) and small-scale business. The assessment will be conducted using both qualitative and quantitative data collection methods, the qualitative data will be collected through focus group discussions (FGD) and key informant interviews (KII).The quantitative data will be collected using individual profiling selecting people who are actively engaged in pastoralism, farming, and small scale business.

The main gap relating to energy delivery and use in South Sudan is that there are no developmental policies and strategies, and the current policies are still at drafting stage. Therefore, at this level is an opportunity to contribute in shaping the direction of the energy sector in the country, since the finding of this research can be used to make some informed decisions by the government and other development agencies. At the Non-Governmental Organization level, the current focus of most NGOs and UN Agencies including ICRC who have been active in the energy sector, is on delivering humanitarian assistance due to the devastating humanitarian situation in the country, coupled with limited funding opportunities relating to the energy sector. Therefore, the engagement in this research will represent an opportunity to the people of South Sudan who are in their need of renewable energy supply. Through this assessment, an action plan for establishing renewable energy and energy efficient strategies, and a financial mechanism will be developed.

Communities in Kaura Local Government Area of Kaduna State were attacked by an unidentified gun-wielding livestock militia on the night of March 24, 2022, according to a statement released by the Kaduna State Government. For unclear reasons, residents of the communities of Adan, Agban, Kagoro, Tsonje, Katanga, and Kadarko were attacked. The government of Kaduna State has enforced a 24-hour curfew. On March 25th, despite the curfew, enraged adolescents in Agban stopped a key highway heading to Jos and other regions, killing travelers of many nationalities, including women, girls, children, and elderly indigenous people.
At least 13 localities have been impacted by the attacks, with an estimated 40,000 people displaced. There have been 67 individuals dead and 2,677 dwellings destroyed. Farmlands have also been targeted, with armed men chopping down crops. Many people (including women, children, and the elderly) have fled to IDP camps in neighboring places such as Zonkwa and Kafanchan in search of safety. Food was the most important need for 61 percent of IDPs in these camps, according to a Red Cross fast assessment, followed by housing, NFI, psychosocial needs, and medical care. The surge of displaced persons has overwhelmed Zonkwa and Kafanchan, with the bulk of those displaced being women, children, and the elderly, while men and youths have remained, taking shelter in the woods and keeping guard at night. 
   This intervention is planned to serve as a lifesaving first step in stabilizing survivors during the initial period before they feel safe returning, as is typical of those in Nigeria's middle region. According to the assessment completed thus far by the Red Cross and local partners in the area, the requirements are fairly diverse due to the nature of the displaced households. The primary needs identified in the assessment findings were food, non-food items, and water and sanitation. The NFIs required include blankets, hand sanitizers, face masks, mattresses, toiletries, mosquito nets, and hygienic supplies such as sanitizers, to name a few. There is also a need for psychosocial/trauma counseling intervention, particularly because the targeted population is regarded as more traumatized and vulnerable in the context and reality of the attacks and their consequences.  The project will consist of supporting 2000 households (14,000 individuals) with multi-purpose cash transfers, NFI procurement and distribution, and psychosocial support.

Currently the Muslim community, which makes up 4.3% of the population (2014 census), is disconnected in its intra-faith understanding and promotion of minority rights. To foster a culture of peace between different faith communities, it is essential that grassroots Islamic leaders and the Muslim community have an increased understanding of their rights as a religious minority. This project will bring together Muslims from different denominations through dialogues, trainings and exposure visits focusing on self-awareness, tolerance and non-violence leading to a greater understanding of themselves and their rights as a minority group. 

Using a rights-based approach, this project will equip and empower Muslim leaders and communities with the knowledge and skills to develop action plans to protect and promote their rights with a united voice. Developing a common understanding of faith and religion (including theology, context and a rights perspective) within each group is a key step to engaging in constructive inter-faith dialogues, and therefore contributing to functional coexistence and a culture of peace.

CAFOD’s long standing partner, CPDMM the Programme for Development and Peace of the Magdalena Medio Region, with national coordination with CINEP, together with CAFOD will implement this project on peace education and culture in Colombia with a youth and gender focus.
Working with 4956 young people and adults (with 52% women and 48% men) in 9 municipalities in the Madgalena Medio Region the project will contribute to an individual and collective peace building and reconciliation culture. It will strengthen the capacities of youth, civil society organizations (CSO), communities and local public institutions to promote peace education and culture, civic coexistence, social solidarity attuned to the environment.
This will be achieved through (1) transforming knowledge, attitudes and  behaviours of adolescents, young people, parents and teachers in 34 schools and promoting peace education and culture, reconciliation, conflict prevention, and peaceful coexistence in their relationships and with their environment, (2) working with civil society organizations and local communities in the Magdalena Medio region to implement pedagogical and cultural initiatives for the transformation of behaviours and to foster peace building and reconciliation, active citizenship and gender equality, as well as social solidarity attuned to the environment and (3) by promoting and disseminating experiences and methodologies  of positive conflict  transformation and the construction of a sustainable regional development through spaces of coexistence, dialogue and inter-sectorial negotiation, with citizen participation.

Caritas Norway, in cooperation with the Catholic Agency for Overseas Development (CAFOD) and Trocaire in Partnership (CTP) and Catholic Diocese of Rumbek (CDoR), Lakes State, will provide improved food security to 5400 IDPs and vulnerable host community members, with a strong focus on empowerment of women. The project will also support conflict prevention and peace building through dialogue and reconciliation activities aligned with the peace work at national level centred on the support to South Sudan Council of Churches and their peace initiatives. This project will provide one of the very sparse humanitarian interventions in the severely underserved target area.
